@comment ** 3.1 >>CALL-CONVENTION                                           **
@comment *********************************************************************
@page
@newsection{3.1,>>CALL-CONVENTION}
@diagram{CDF >>CALL-CONVENTION,CDF-CALL,CDF-CALL,None}@p This directive instructs the compiler how to treat references to program names and may be used to determine other details for interacting with a function or program. There are four options with COBOL being the default.
@enumerate
@p @item COBOL (the default) the program name is treated as a COBOL word that maps to the externalised name program to be called, cancelled or referenced in the program-address-identifier, applying the same mapping rules as for a program name for which no AS phrase is specified.
@p @item EXTERN the program name is treated as an external reference.
@p @item STDCALL. < more info needed >
@p @item STATIC the program name is called as a included element and not dynamically which is the normal default.
@end enumerate
@comment *********************************************************************
@comment ** 3.2 COPY                                                        **
@comment *********************************************************************
@page
@newsection{3.2,COPY}
@diagram{CDF COPY Statement,CDF-COPY,CDF-COPY,None}
@diagram{CDF COPY Phrase-Clause,CDF-COPY-Phrase,CDF-COPY-Phrase,None}
@diagram{CDF COPY String-Clause,CDF-COPY-String,CDF-COPY-String,None}
@enumerate
@p @item @syntax{COPY} statements are used to import copybooks (@pxref{Copybooks}) into a program.
@p @item @syntax{COPY} statements may be used anywhere within a COBOL program where the code contained within the copybook would be syntactically valid.
@p @item The optional @syntaxidx{SUPPRESS} clause (with or without the optional @syntaxidx{PRINTING} reserved word) is valid syntactically but is non-functional.  It is supported to facilitate compatibility with source code written for other versions of COBOL.
@p @item There is no difference between the use of the word @syntax{IN} and the word @syntax{OF} --- use the one you prefer.
@p @item A period is absolutely mandatory at the end of every @syntax{COPY} statement, even if the statement occurs within the scope of another one where a period might appear disruptive, such as within the scope of an @syntaxref{IF} statement.  This mandatory period at the end of the statement will not, however, affect the statement scope in which the @syntax{COPY} occurs.
@p @item Both @term{pseudo-text-2} and @term{partial-word-2} may be null.
@p @item All @syntax{COPY} statements are located and the contents of the corresponding copybooks inserted into the program source code before the actual compilation process begins.  If a copybook contains a @syntax{COPY} statement, the copybook insertion process will be repeated to resolve the embedded @syntax{COPY}.  This will continue until no unresolved @syntax{COPY} statements remain.  At that point, actual program compilation will begin.
@p @item @xref{Locating Copybooks}, for the specific rules on how copybooks are located by the compiler.
@p @item The optional @syntaxidx{REPLACING} clause allows for one or more of either of the following kinds of text replacements to be made:
@table @asis
@p @item @clause{Phrase-Clause}
@p Replacement of one or more complete reserved words, user-defined identifiers or literals; the following points apply to this option:
@itemize
@p @item This option cannot be used to replace part of a word, identifier or literal.
@p @item Whatever precedes the @syntax{BY} will be referred to here as the search string.
@p @item Single-item search strings can be specified by coding the @syntax{@term{identifier-1}}, @syntax{@term{literal-1}} or @syntax{@term{word-1}} being replaced.
@p @item Multiple-item search strings can be specified using the @syntax{==@term{pseudo-text-1}==} option.  For example, to replace all occurrences of @syntax{UPON PRINTER}, you would specify @syntax{==UPON PRINTER==}.
@p @item The replacement string, which follows the @syntax{BY}, may be specified using any of the four options.
@p @item If the replacement string is a multiple-item phrase or is to be deleted altogether, you must use the @syntax{==@term{pseudo-text-2}==} option.  If @syntax{@term{pseudo-text-2}} is null (in other words, the replacement text is specified as @syntax{====}), all encountered occurrences of the search string will be deleted.
@end itemize
@item @clause{String-Clause}
@p Using this, you may replace character sequences that occur at the beginning (@syntaxidx{LEADING}) or end (@syntaxidx{TRAILING}) of reserved or user-defined words.  For example, to change all words of the form "0100-xxxxxx" to "020-xxxxxx", code @syntax{LEADING ==0100-== BY ==020-==}.  To simply remove all "0100-" prefixes from words, code @syntax{LEADING ==0100-== BY ====}.
@end table
@end enumerate
@comment *********************************************************************
@comment ** 3.3 REPLACE                                                     **
@comment *********************************************************************
@page
@newsection{3.3,REPLACE}
@diagram{CDF REPLACE Statement (Format 1),CDF-REPLACE-1,CDF-REPLACE-1,None}
@diagram{CDF REPLACE Statement (Format 2),CDF-REPLACE-2,CDF-REPLACE-2,None}
@diagram{CDF REPLACE Phrase-Clause,CDF-REPLACE-Phrase,CDF-REPLACE-Phrase,None}
@diagram{CDF REPLACE String-Clause,CDF-REPLACE-String,CDF-REPLACE-String,None}
@enumerate 1
@p @item The @syntax{REPLACE} statement provides a mechanism for changing all or part of one or more GnuCOBOL statements.
@p @item A period is absolutely mandatory at the end of every @syntax{REPLACE} statement (either format), even if the statement occurs within the scope of another one where a period might appear disruptive (such as within the scope of an @syntaxref{IF} statement; the period will not, however, affect the statement scope in which the @syntax{REPLACE} occurs.
@p @item The following points apply to Format 1 of the @syntax{REPLACE} statement:
@enumerate A
@p @item Format 1 of the @syntax{REPLACE} statement can be used to make changes to program source code in much the same way as the @syntaxidx{REPLACING} option of the @syntax{COPY} statement can, via these options:
@table @asis
@p @item @clause{Phrase-Clause}
@p Replace one or more complete reserved words, user-defined identifiers or literals; the following points apply to this option:
@itemize @bullet
@p @item This option cannot be used to replace part of a word, identifier or literal.
@p @item Whatever precedes the @syntax{BY} will be referred to here as the search string.
@p @item Search strings on @syntax{REPLACE} are always specified using the @syntax{==@term{pseudo-text-1}==} option.  For example, to replace all occurrences of @syntax{UPON PRINTER}, you would specify @syntax{==UPON PRINTER==}.
@p @item The replacement string, which follows the @syntax{BY}, is specified using the @syntax{==@term{pseudo-text-2}==} option.  If @syntax{@term{pseudo-text-2}} is null (in other words, the replacement text is specified as @syntax{====}), all encountered occurrences of the search string will be deleted.
@end itemize
@item @clause{String-Clause}
@p Using this, you may replace character sequences that occur at the beginning (@syntaxidx{LEADING}) or end (@syntaxidx{TRAILING}) of reserved or user-defined words.  For example, to change all words of the form "0100-xxxxxx" to "020-xxxxxx", code @syntax{LEADING ==0100-== BY ==020-==}.  To simply remove all "0100-" prefixes from words, code @syntax{LEADING ==0100-== BY ====}.
@end table
@item Once a Format 1 @syntax{REPLACE} statement is encountered in the currently-compiling source file, Replace Mode becomes active, and the change(s) specified by that statement will be automatically made on all subsequent source statements the compiler reads from the file.
@p @item Replace Mode remains in-effect --- continuing to make source code changes --- until another Format 1 @syntax{REPLACE} is encountered, the end of currently compiling program source file is reached or a Format 2 @syntax{REPLACE} statement is encountered.
@p @item When a Format 1 @syntax{REPLACE} statement with the @syntaxidx{ALSO} keyword is encountered without Replace Mode being currently active, the effect will be as if the @syntax{ALSO} had not been specified.  If Replace Mode already was in effect, the effect will be to "push" the current change specification(s) onto the top of a stack and add the specification(s) of the new statement to those that were already in effect.
@p @item When a Format 1 @syntax{REPLACE} without the @syntax{ALSO} keyword is encountered, any stacked change specification(s), if any, will be discarded and the currently in-effect change specification(s), if any, will be replaced by those of the new statement.
@p @item When the end of the currently-compiling source file is reached, Replace Mode is deactivated and any stacked replace specifications will be discarded --- compilation of the next source file (if any) will begin with Replace Mode inactive and no change specification(s) on the stack.
@end enumerate
@item The following points apply to Format 2 of the @syntax{REPLACE} statement:
@enumerate A
@p @item If Replace Mode is currently inactive, the Format 2 REPLACE statement will be ignored.
@p @item If Replace Mode is currently active, a @syntax{REPLACE OFF.} will deactivate Replace Mode and discard any replace specification(s) on the stack.  The compiler will henceforth operate as if no @syntax{REPLACE} had ever been encountered, until such time as another Format 1 @syntax{REPLACE} is encountered.
@p @item If Replace Mode is currently active, a @syntax{REPLACE LAST OFF.} will replace the current replace specification(s) with those popped off the top of the stack.  If there were no replace specification(s) on the stack, the effect will be as if a @syntax{REPLACE OFF.} had been coded.
@end enumerate
@end enumerate
