@comment ** 3.4 >>DEFINE Directive                                          **
@comment *********************************************************************
@page
@newsection{3.4,>>DEFINE}
@diagram{CDF >>DEFINE Directive,CDF-DEFINE,CDF-DEFINE,None}@p Use the @directive{>>DEFINE} to create CDF variables and (optionally) assign them either literal or environment variable values.
@enumerate
@p @item The reserved word @syntax{AS} is optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of this word has no effect upon the program.
@p @item CDF variables defined in this way become undefined once an @syntax{END PROGRAM} or @syntax{END FUNCTION} directive is encountered in the input source.
@p @item The @directive{>>DEFINE} is one way to create CDF variables that may be processed by other CDF statements such as @syntaxref{>>IF}.  The @directiveref{>>SET} provides another way to create them.
@p @item CDF variable names follow the rules for standard GnuCOBOL user-defined names, and may not duplicate any CDF reserved word.  CDF variable names may duplicate COBOL reserved words, provided the @syntaxidx{CONSTANT} option is not specified, but such names are not recommended.
@p @item The @syntax{CONSTANT} option is valid only in conjunction with @term{literal-1}.  When @syntax{CONSTANT} is specified, the CDF variable that is created may be used within your regular COBOL code as if it were a literal value.  Without this option, the CDF variable may only be referenced on other CDF statements.  The @syntaxidx{OFF} option is used to create a variable without assigning it any value.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{PARAMETER} option is used to create a variable whose value is that of the environment variable of the same name.  Note that this value assignment occurs at compilation time, not program execution time.
@p @item In the absence of the @syntaxidx{OVERRIDE} option, @term{cdf-variable-1} must not yet have been defined.  When the @syntax{OVERRIDE} option is specified, @term{cdf-variable-1} will be created with the specified value, if it had not yet been defined.  If it had already been defined, it will be redefined with the new value.
@end enumerate
